        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:Sounds Wonderful"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:Sounds Wonderful<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~JimDarkmagic" class="author" title="author name and user ID">JimDarkmagic (1339257) </a> | about 4 months ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=4904573&cid=46498627">(#46498627)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_46498627" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>The DOE already passed "Gainful Employment" rules once.  The first time around, a group representing the for-profit colleges sued the DOE and got the teeth ripped out of the rules.  The judge decided the metrics that lead to punishments didn't have enough factual basis to back them up, so they were thrown out.  These rules appear to the the second attempt, likely prepared with more thought to defending themselves against the schools with deep pockets.</p><p>Googling "gainful employment rules" or "gainful employment rules stuck down" will likely provide more information.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_46498627">
